### FUD #2: [Scalability / Performance]

**What they say:**
"[Product] doesn't scale. Once you get to [X users/documents/data], performance degrades and it becomes unusable."

**Example (Confluence about Notion):**
"Notion slows down once you have 1,000+ pages. Our customers have millions of pages with no performance issues."

**Truth level:**
- [ ] Complete lie
- [x] Was true in 2020, not true today (we've improved performance)
- [ ] Partially true but exaggerated
- [ ] Factually accurate

**Why they say it:**
- [Uncertainty tactic]: Makes prospects worry about future
- [Target audience]: VPs, technical buyers planning for growth
- [When they use it]: Enterprise deals, when discussing scale

**How to counter:**

**1. Acknowledge historical context (if applicable):**
"Early versions of [Product] (2018-2020) did have performance issues at scale. Fair criticism back then."

**2. Present current reality:**
"We've since rebuilt our infrastructure. Today, [Enterprise customer] has 50,000+ pages with sub-second load times. [Another customer] has 5,000 users with no performance degradation."

**3. Provide proof:**
"Happy to show you our performance benchmarks: [data on load times at scale]. We can also connect you with [Large customer] to discuss their experience at [X scale]."

**4. Flip it (if applicable):**
"Confluence's 'millions of pages' claim is true - they've been around since 2004. But ask customers about search performance with millions of pages. We often hear 'Confluence search is slow' (G2 reviews). Quantity ≠ quality."

**Supporting materials:**
- Performance benchmarks: [link]
- Enterprise customer case study: [link]
- G2 reviews mentioning performance: [link]
- Technical architecture overview: [link]

